04386nam a22005655i 9780226020570DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20082008ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226020570  a(DE-B1597)524783  a(OCoLC)304436418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN1995.9.H95bA5413 2008 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/65562221 aAndriopoulos, Stefan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPossessed :bHypnotic Crimes, Corporate Fiction, and the Invention of Cinema /cStefan Andriopoulos. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b13 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCinema and Modernity00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tI. TALES OF HYPNOTIC CRIME -- tII. INVISIBLE CORPORATE BODIES -- tIII. STAGING THE HYPNOTIC CRIME -- tIV. BERNHEIM, CALIGARI, MABUSE: CINEMA AND HYPNOTISM -- tV. HUMAN AND CORPORATE BODIES IN BROCH AND KAFKA -- tEPILOGUE -- tAPPENDIX A. FILMOGRAPHY -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSilent cinema and contemporaneous literature explored themes of mesmerism, possession, and the ominous agency of corporate bodies that subsumed individual identities. At the same time, critics accused film itself of exerting a hypnotic influence over spellbound audiences. Stefan Andriopoulos shows that all this anxiety over being governed by an outside force was no marginal oddity, but rather a pervasive concern in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Tracing this preoccupation through the period’s films—as well as its legal, medical, and literary texts—Andriopoulos pays particular attention to the terrifying notion of murder committed against one’s will. He returns us to a time when medical researchers described the hypnotized subject as a medium who could be compelled to carry out violent crimes, and when films like The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari and Dr. Mabuse, the Gambler famously portrayed the hypnotist’s seemingly unlimited power on the movie screen. Juxtaposing these medicolegal and cinematic scenarios with modernist fiction, Andriopoulos also develops an innovative reading of Kafka’s novels, which center on the merging of human and corporate bodies. Blending theoretical sophistication with scrupulous archival research and insightful film analysis, Possessed adds a new dimension to our understanding of today’s anxieties about the onslaught of visual media and the expanding reach of vast corporations that seem to absorb our own identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCorporationsxCorrupt practices. 0aHypnotism and crime. 0aHypnotism in literature. 0aHypnotism in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  asilent film, cinema, mesmerism, possession, haunting, hypnotism, identity, cabinet of dr caligari, mabuse the gambler, murder, crime, free will, control, agency, kafka, bernheim, broch, autonomy, modernism, literature, suggestion, german expressionism, somnambulism, sleepwalking, vision, hallucination, nonfiction, art, berlin, babelsberg.1 aAndriopoulos, Stefan.1 aJansen, Peter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226020570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226020570/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles